<TITLE> Case filed against 36 'Razakars', including top JI leader </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Bagerhat, Jan 4 (bdnews24.com)  The wife of a slain freedom fighter filed a case against 36 alleged Razakars in Bagerhat on Monday, on charges of murdering freedom fighters, looting and arson during the Liberation War in 1971. The accused include top-ranking Jamaat-e-Islami leader Maulana Abul Kalam Muhammad Yousuf. Mosammat Khadija Begum, of South Razapur village in Sharankhola upazila, wife of martyred freedom fighter Ismail Hossain Hawlader, filed the case with the Bagerhat additional chief judicial magistrate's court. Judge Abdus Salam Khan ordered the Sharankhola police to record the case. According to the complainant, the accused, led by Maulana Yousuf, set up a camp at a building at Sharankhola and killed many locals including freedom fighters. On June 7 1971, the complainant's husband and a companion Asmat Munshi fell into the hands of the accused, as they and other freedom fighters attacked the Razakar camp and exchanged gunfire. Later, the accused hacked them to death with sharp weapons and threw them into a canal, said Khadija's statement. On the next day (June 8), the accused stormed into Khadija's house, looted gold, crops and cash and set fire to her house. Ismail's body was recovered after two days but Asmat's body is yet to be found, the statement said. Sharankhola police chief Nizam Uddin said the police are yet receive any document concerning the case. "We will initiate action as soon as we receive official instructions," he said. bdnews24
